Starting from September 15, 2021, vaccination will be mandatory for: 
- all medical and non-medical staff in hospitals, clinics, retirement homes, establishments for people with disabilities;
- all professionals or volunteers who work in contact with the elderly or fragile, including at home.

About 555,000 people under the age of 55 received a first injection with the AstraZeneca vaccine in France. In its opinion of April 9 2021, the French National Authority for Health recommends the implementation of a new strategy vaccine for these people:
- they will not receive a second dose of AstraZeneca vaccine within 12 weeks after the first dose; 
- Instead, they will receive a dose of an mRNA vaccine (Pfizer-BioNTech or Moderna) 12 weeks after first dose of AstraZeneca vaccine.

The injection of a third dose of the vaccine for severely immunocompromised individuals in France is possible 4 weeks after the second dose, or as soon as possible for people who have already exceeded this time. The third dose, similarly to the first two, should be administered in treatment centers for immunocompromised patients. This includes individuals:
- who have received an organ or hematopoietic stem cell transplant;
- under lymphopenic chemotherapy;
- treated with strong immunosuppressive drugs, such as antimetabolites (cellcept, myfortic, mycophenolate mofetil, imurel, azathioprine) and AntiCD20 (rituximab: Mabthera, Rixathon, Truxima);
- chronic dialysis patients after consulting their doctor who will decide on the need for appropriate examinations;
- on a case-by-case basis, people on immunosuppressants not falling within the above-mentioned categories or carriers of primary immunodeficiency.

The full list of French people who must be vaccinated was published on August 4, 2021. According to that, the population for whom vaccination is compulsory by September 15, 2021: 
- All staff (including administrative) of health establishments, medico-social establishments (EHPAD, USLD, independent residences, disability structures with or without accommodation and including non-medical), social establishments attached to a health establishment (LHSS , LAM, CSAPA, CAARUD, CLAT, CEGGID);
- Home helpers working with people receiving APA or PCH, in the context of home services or as employees of private employers;
- Staff of medical transport companies (including approved taxis);
- All professions in Book IV of the CSP, contracted or not, and professions using titles, as well as their employees (eg medical secretaries, dental assistants);
- All health students;
- SDIS-Pompiers (professionals and volunteers);
- Occupational health service personnel.
- People with a contraindication to vaccination will be exempted from the vaccination obligation. 

Unvaccinated personnel will have until September 15, 2021 to do so, or even until October 15, 2021 if they have already received a first dose of vaccine, and subject to presenting a negative test. A certificate of vaccination status will then be issued to them. Checks will be carried out from September 15, 2021.

