On April 9 in France, the Agence Française de Développement launched “COVID-19 – Health in Common” – a €1.2 billion initiative in response to the worldwide public health crisis caused by the COVID-19 pandemic." The initiative is the result of a collaboration between the French President and his African peers and prioritizes "the 19 priority countries for French aid in Africa, the ocean basins (Madagascar, Comoros and Haiti) and the Middle East. 

The main objectives of the initiative are the following:
(1) Reinforcing regional epidemiological surveillance networks;
(2) Contributing to national COVID-19 response plans in African countries;
(3) Supporting the main French actors in the response to COVID-19 (NGOs, foundations, networks, research bodies, etc.);
(4) Providing budget support for the reinforcement of healthcare systems.

On the 24 February 2020, the Regional Health Agency (ARS) of the Grand Est region of France made a press release detailing a system of health monitoring for returned travellers. The management system targeted returned travellers from the Veneto and Lombardy regions of Italy, mainland China, Hong Kong, Macau, Singapore and South Korea. If returned travellers displayed any symptoms, they were required to contact a centre for assessment and possible testing, and if confirmed ARS staff would trace close contacts. Positive cases were then instructed to self-isolate for 14 days and avoid all contact with fragile people (pregnant women, chronically ill, elderly people, etc.);
avoid going to places where there are vulnerable people (hospitals, maternity hospitals, accommodation facilities for the elderly, etc.);
Avoid any non-essential outing (large gatherings, restaurants, cinema, etc.).

From December 20 2020, The government of France is empowered to prescribe quarantine or placement and maintenance in isolation:
a) Persons who cannot justify, on their arrival, the result of a test or biological examination for virological screening carried out less than 72 hours before boarding, not concluding that there was contamination by covid-19;
b) Persons returning to the national territory from an area hosting ski resorts listed in Appendix 2 (in Spain, the autonomous communities of Andalusia, Aragon, Catalonia and Navarre, in Switzerland, the cantons of Grisons, Jura, Neuchâtel, Uri, Valais and Vaud.), who cannot justify on their arrival either the professional reason for their stay in this area or the result of a virological screening test or biological examination carried out less than 72 hours earlier that does not conclude that contamination by covid-19 is present;

From March 20, 2020 until April 19, 2020 in France, in order to speed up and streamline the transport of goods during the pandemic and avoid shortages, the Ministry of Ecological and Solidarity Transition authorized international and national road freight transport companies to 
(1) Increase the daily driving time, within the limit of ten hours per day or eleven hours per day twice a week;
(2) Increase the weekly driving time, within the limit of sixty hours per week and one hundred and two hours over two consecutive weeks, provided that these increases comply with the legal and regulatory provisions relating to working time and rest applicable to conductors.

On May 31, 2020, the French government announced that as of June 2, 2020, any gathering, meeting or activity that simultaneously brings together more than 10 people on the public highway or in a place open to the public is prohibited throughout the Republic. This prohibition does not apply to
_to gatherings or activities organized for professional purposes ;
_to passenger transport services;
_to establishments receiving the public in which this reception is not prohibited;
_to funeral ceremonies organized outside establishments receiving _the public and for which this reception is not prohibited.

On May 31, 2020, the French government announced that as of June 2, 2020, any gathering, meeting or activity that simultaneously brings together more than 10 people on the public highway or in a place open to the public is prohibited throughout the Republic. This prohibition does not apply to
_to gatherings or activities organized for professional purposes ;
_to passenger transport services;
_to establishments receiving the public in which this reception is not prohibited;
_to funeral ceremonies organized outside establishments receiving _the public and for which this reception is not prohibited. UPDATE: On July 11, 2020, the government announced the end of the health emergency. Any gathering, meeting or activity on the public highway, or in a place open to the public, must be organized in conditions that allow the respect of "barrier gestures".
Persons organizing this type of event involving more than 10 people at the same time must send a prior declaration to the competent Prefect containing the following information
-the name, first name and address of the organizers
-the purpose of the event, the place, date and time of the gathering of the groups invited to take part
-the projected itinerary;
-the measures implemented to ensure compliance with the "barrier gestures".

On July 27, 2020, the Prime Minister announced that on August 15, 2020, the Prefect may exceptionally authorize events bringing together more than 5,000 people, after analyzing the risk factors and in particular:
_the general health situation and that of the territories concerned ;
_the measures implemented by the organizer to ensure compliance with the "barrier measures";
_the measures specifically taken by the organizer to prevent the risk of propagation of the virus specific to _the event concerned beyond 5,000 people.

On November 7th, 2020, France's summary judge specifies the applicable rules found in the decree of October 29, 2020:
- all places of worship remain open;
- the faithful can take part in funerals and weddings up to a limit of 30 and 6 people respectively, but also go there to worship on an individual basis, in particular during their other authorized trips;
- ministers of religion can freely take part in religious ceremonies, in particular to ensure their retransmission, and to receive the faithful individually, as well as they can go to their homes. UPDATE: On November 7th, 2020, the summary judge specifies the applicable rules found in the decree of October 29, 2020:
